The commission's recommendation for federal standards on birth certificates and IDs, including driver's licenses, has sparked concerns in several states.
Senator Lamar Alexander criticized new rules in a military spending bill, labeling them as a burden on state governments.
Some states are considering legal challenges or outright disobedience.
Immigrant rights groups oppose the REAL ID Act, arguing it won't enhance security.
The bill aims to tighten regulations on driver's licenses, with implications for illegal immigrants.
Proponents claim it will deter terrorism, while critics fear privacy violations and a de facto national ID system.
